722fc933-d894-426e-a306-50de1252ffde.text: PRELIMINARY EVALUATION OF SENTIN EL - 2 BOTTOM OF ATMOSPHERE REFLECTANCE USING THE 6S V CODE IN BEIJING AR E A Jing Chen, Yingjie Li * , Qingmiao M a , Xiaoqi Shen, Anjing Zhao, Jiasheng Li School of Geography, Geomatics and Planning, Jiangsu Normal University, 101 Shanghai Road, Xuzhou, Jiangsu 221116, China * Correspond ence: maqingmiao@jsnu.edu.cn ABSTRACT In this study, the Sentinel - 2A Bottom Of Atmosphere ( BOA )reflectance imageries over Beijing area from Dec 2016 to Nov 2017 were generated by the Sen2Cor processor and evaluated using the AERONET measurements and the 6SV code . The result show s a poor correlation between the Sen2Cor retrieved AOT and the ground data with R = 0.289possibly because of the limitation of the AOT algorithm. T he errors of Sen 2Cor retrieved AOT and water vapor pressure have a great effect on the BOA reflectance and spectral indices such as NDVI . The highest relative uncertainty of the Sen2Cor BOA reflectance is 37 .76 % for B01 and the lowest correlation is 0. 859 for B09 . The resultalso shows that a high - accuracy atmospheric correction is still crucial and u rgent for the Sentinel - 2 A data . INTRODUCTION The Bottom Of Atmosphere (BOA) reflectance , also known as the surface reflectance, i.e., satellite derived Top Of A tmosphere (TOA) reflectance corrected for the sc attering and absorbing effects of atmospheric gases and aerosols, is widely used to monitor the land surface reliably and generate the greater majority of global land products [1]. However, due to the c omplexity of scattering and absorbing properties of ae rosols , it is still difficult to correct the atmospheric effect for the optical satellite imagery . Sentinel - 2 is a European wide - swath, high - resolution,multi - spectral imaging mission. The full mission comprisestwin satellit es, Sentinel - 2A and Sentinel - 2B ( S2A and S2B), which were launched on Jun. 23, 2015 and Mar. 07, 2017, respectively [2]. Each satellite carries a Multi - Spectral Instrument (MSI) , which can make a significant contribution to land monitoring and products generation w ith its high revisit f requency ( 10 or 5 days at the equator with one or two satellite s , respectively ), wide swath (~290 km), and highresolution ( up to 10 m) i magery [ 2 ] . In 2017, Gascon et al. evaluated the S 2A p roducts , and found that t he BOA reflectance differences was up t o 0.04 which lead to a Normalized D ifference Vegetation Index (NDVI) uncertainty up to 0.06 [ 3 ] . Li and Ma also evaluated the S 2A BOA reflectance using 6SV code at t he AErosol RObotic NETwork (AERONET) site, Egbert, in Canada [ 4 ]. CONCLUSION In this study, the BOA reflectance over five AERONET sites in Beijing area from Dec 2016 to Nov 2017 , obtained by the S2A MSI and corrected by Sen2Cor was evaluated using the 6SV atmospherically corrected reflectance. The atmosphericparameters (e.g., AOD and WV) for the 6SV model werecollected from the AERONET site. The evaluation resultshows that due to the limita tion of DDV algorithm, the Sen 2Cor retrieved AOT has a poor correlation with the AERONET data . The errors of the retrieved AOT and WVP have an effect on the BOA reflectance and spectral indices. The highest relative uncertainty can be over 37% and the lowe st correlation is 0. 859 . In summary, for the applications of S2A MSI data , a high - accuracy atmospheric correction isstill very crucial. The surface reflectance corrected bySen2Cor should be treated with some degree of caution,especially for the visible bands and spectral indice s.
